00:00:29.490 --> 00:00:35.460
Back to cavity QED, back to
the fully quantized radiation

00:00:35.460 --> 00:00:38.125
field, back to vacuum
Rabi oscillation.

00:00:42.700 --> 00:00:45.730
Let me just recapitulate and
sort of make the transition

00:00:45.730 --> 00:00:48.650
from this intense
discussion about homework

00:00:48.650 --> 00:00:52.560
to the intellectually
stimulating discussion

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:55.060
about atoms and photons.

00:00:55.060 --> 00:00:57.490
So in the semiclassical
description

00:00:57.490 --> 00:01:00.230
of the electromagnetic
field, photons

00:01:00.230 --> 00:01:02.450
can only be emitted
because we have

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:05.310
a Hamiltonian with the
semiclassical electric field.

00:01:05.310 --> 00:01:08.130
So if you don't drive the
system with an electric field,

00:01:08.130 --> 00:01:11.090
you cannot stimulate
the emission of photons.

00:01:11.090 --> 00:01:14.200
But we know this is
not what happens.

00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:16.630
Photons are emitted
into empty space,

00:01:16.630 --> 00:01:18.690
photons are emitted
into a vacuum.

00:01:18.690 --> 00:01:22.340
And for that we needed
a quantized description

00:01:22.340 --> 00:01:23.940
of the electromagnetic field.

00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:26.120
We did field
quantization, and we

00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:29.170
have now our
quantized Hamiltonian.

00:01:29.170 --> 00:01:33.210
And on Monday I
started to discuss

00:01:33.210 --> 00:01:35.285
what is sort of the
paradigmatic situation,

00:01:35.285 --> 00:01:39.030
the paradigmatic example,
for how you should think

00:01:39.030 --> 00:01:41.910
about the vacuum and how you
should think about emission

00:01:41.910 --> 00:01:43.710
of photons into the vacuum.

00:01:43.710 --> 00:01:46.880
And these are the
vacuum Rabi oscillation

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:49.780
described by the
Jaynes-Cummings model.

00:01:49.780 --> 00:01:52.635
So the situation
which I have in mind,

00:01:52.635 --> 00:01:54.010
or which you should
have in mind,

00:01:54.010 --> 00:01:57.370
is an idealized
situation, but it

00:01:57.370 --> 00:02:00.450
has been realized
experimentally.

00:02:00.450 --> 00:02:04.130
And some of those
idealized experiments

00:02:04.130 --> 00:02:06.620
were recognized
with the Nobel Prize

00:02:06.620 --> 00:02:08.310
research of Haroche
and Dave Wineland.

00:02:08.310 --> 00:02:11.039
So the situation
is we have an atom,

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:15.610
but it only talks to one mode
of the electromagnetic field,

00:02:15.610 --> 00:02:17.340
and we make sure
that the atom only

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:20.580
talks to one mode of the
electromagnetic field

00:02:20.580 --> 00:02:22.980
not by eliminating
other modes; they exist.

00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:26.460
I mean, an atom can emit
upwards and downwards.

00:02:26.460 --> 00:02:32.340
But we surround it with a cavity
which has such a small mode

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:37.460
volume, it has such a small
volume, that the single photon

00:02:37.460 --> 00:02:40.620
Rabi frequency is
huge, and therefore

00:02:40.620 --> 00:02:44.410
the emission into
this one single mode

00:02:44.410 --> 00:02:47.970
dominates over the emission
into all other modes.

00:02:50.510 --> 00:02:54.410
So this is a condition that the
single photon Rabi frequency

00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:56.830
has to be larger than gamma.

00:02:56.830 --> 00:02:58.900
And, of course, we
also have to make sure

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:02.840
that the system is idealized
so the loss of photons because

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:05.240
of losses in the mirror,
or finite reflectivity

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:08.060
in the mirror, also
has to be smaller.

00:03:08.060 --> 00:03:11.200
So that means for
several Rabi periods

00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:15.600
we have a system which has only
two parts, a two-level atom

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:17.740
and one single
mode of the cavity.

00:03:20.520 --> 00:03:23.810
So that's the system
we have in mind,

00:03:23.810 --> 00:03:26.580
and we discussed
the Hamiltonian.

00:03:30.070 --> 00:03:34.320
We saw that the Hilbert
space of the atom

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:38.020
is excited in ground state, the
Hilbert space of the photons

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:42.157
is spent by the
[? flux ?] states,

00:03:42.157 --> 00:03:44.740
but what happens is-- so there's
an infinite number of states,

00:03:44.740 --> 00:03:47.770
because of the infinite number
of states of the photon field--

00:03:47.770 --> 00:03:53.710
but what happens is the
Hamiltonian couples only

00:03:53.710 --> 00:03:57.540
an excited state with n photons
to a ground state with n

00:03:57.540 --> 00:03:59.080
plus 1 photons.

00:03:59.080 --> 00:04:03.890
So the whole Hilbert
space is segmented now

00:04:03.890 --> 00:04:09.250
into just pairs of states
labeled by the index n.

00:04:09.250 --> 00:04:15.320
So after so much work, we are
back to a two-level system.

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:19.810
And here is our
two-level Hamiltonian.

00:04:19.810 --> 00:04:22.350
And, well, a
two-level system does

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:24.120
oscillations between
the two levels.

00:04:24.120 --> 00:04:26.220
Rabi oscillations, no surprise.

00:04:26.220 --> 00:04:28.910
And this is what I
want to discuss now.

00:04:28.910 --> 00:04:36.060
But the new feature is that
these are really, well,

00:04:36.060 --> 00:04:38.950
these are now really two levels.

00:04:38.950 --> 00:04:41.910
Each of them is
the combined state

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:44.620
of the atom and the
quantized radiation field.

00:04:44.620 --> 00:04:48.950
So now we have included in
our two-level description

00:04:48.950 --> 00:04:51.950
the quantum state of the
electromagnetic field.

00:04:56.910 --> 00:05:08.930
So first you should realize that
this Hamiltonian is absolutely

00:05:08.930 --> 00:05:13.540
identical to spn 1/2
in magnetic fields.

00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:27.490
And you can recognize
by [? comparing ?]

00:05:27.490 --> 00:05:29.740
this Hamiltonian, this
matrix, to the matrices

00:05:29.740 --> 00:05:33.880
we discussed for spn 1/2
in the magnetic field,

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:39.720
that this corresponds
to the situation

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:44.540
where this spn 1/2
had a transverse field

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:49.520
in the x direction which
caused a precession from spn

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:51.310
up to spn down.

00:05:51.310 --> 00:05:54.930
And this x component
of the field

00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:58.700
corresponds now to the single
photon Rabi frequency times

00:05:58.700 --> 00:05:59.880
n plus 1.

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:02.780
That's the off diagonal
matrix element in this matrix.

00:06:07.050 --> 00:06:08.750
The thing which we
have to discuss,

00:06:08.750 --> 00:06:12.330
and I will focus later,
is that it depends on n.

00:06:12.330 --> 00:06:15.970
So for each pairs of state
labeled by n, the photon

00:06:15.970 --> 00:06:21.530
number, we have a different
off diagonal matrix element.

00:06:21.530 --> 00:06:27.600
But let's discuss first the most
important and simplest case.

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:32.640
Let's assume we
are on resonance,

00:06:32.640 --> 00:06:42.520
and we want to assume
that we have a vacuum.

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:51.070
Then our Hamiltonian
is simply this.

00:06:51.070 --> 00:06:56.690
And when we prepare the system
in an initial state, which

00:06:56.690 --> 00:07:06.250
is an excited state with
no photon in the vacuum,

00:07:06.250 --> 00:07:11.180
then we'll have
oscillations to the ground

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:12.120
state with one photon.

00:07:15.360 --> 00:07:17.740
These oscillations are
exactly the oscillations

00:07:17.740 --> 00:07:19.262
we saw on the spn 1/2 system.

00:07:19.262 --> 00:07:20.470
We can just map the solution.

00:07:20.470 --> 00:07:23.640
I'm not really
writing anything here.

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:28.750
So what we obtain is the famous
vacuum Rabi oscillations.

00:07:31.274 --> 00:07:38.220
where the probability to
be in the excited state

00:07:38.220 --> 00:07:46.100
oscillates with the single
photon Rabi frequency omega 1.

00:07:46.100 --> 00:07:48.940
I think there's a little bit
of an ambiguity in language.

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:50.985
Is it the single
photon Rabi frequency?

00:07:50.985 --> 00:07:53.700
or is it the vacuum
Rabi frequency?

00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:56.580
Because there's always
the question about plus

00:07:56.580 --> 00:07:59.010
minus one photon because
we start in the excited

00:07:59.010 --> 00:08:01.170
state without photon
so you want to say

00:08:01.170 --> 00:08:02.980
it's a vacuum Rabi frequency.

00:08:02.980 --> 00:08:05.850
But then you have the ground
state with one photon,

00:08:05.850 --> 00:08:08.040
and this photon is
reabsorbed and then

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:10.840
you may want to call it the
one photon Rabi frequency.

00:08:10.840 --> 00:08:15.060
So I leave it to you, but it's
called vacuum Rabi oscillation

00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:18.710
and this Rabi frequency is
usually referred to as the one

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:21.860
photon Rabi frequency
because we obtained the Rabi

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:24.889
frequency by calculating
the electric field

00:08:24.889 --> 00:08:25.680
of a single photon.

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:34.140
So the Rabi oscillations
which we are observing now

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:40.130
correspond to the periodic
spontaneous emission

00:08:40.130 --> 00:08:43.370
and re-absorption
of the same photon.

00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:46.430
There's only one photon
which is spontaneously

00:08:46.430 --> 00:08:51.450
emitted and reabsorbed in
a completely reversible

00:08:51.450 --> 00:08:54.560
coherent way, and the
time evolution is unitary.

00:09:12.350 --> 00:09:22.390
So it's a periodic
spontaneous emission

00:09:22.390 --> 00:09:25.180
and re-absorption
of the same photon.

00:09:38.630 --> 00:09:40.595
This has been
experimentally observed.

00:09:43.220 --> 00:09:45.280
Actually, let me back up.

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:51.875
Experiments are done in
the microwave regime.

00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:58.460
The leading groups are,
well, in the older days,

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:00.030
Dan Kleppner, Herbert
[? Weidner, ?]

00:10:00.030 --> 00:10:02.000
and Serge Haroche.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.830
And this involves Rydberg atoms.

00:10:04.830 --> 00:10:13.685
Rydberg atoms in
superconducting high q cavities.

00:10:17.550 --> 00:10:20.150
And those Rydberg
atoms, because things

00:10:20.150 --> 00:10:22.910
scale with n and n squared,
the principal quantum number,

00:10:22.910 --> 00:10:24.860
have a fantastically
strong coupling

00:10:24.860 --> 00:10:27.120
to the electromagnetic field.

00:10:27.120 --> 00:10:29.130
And there is a
homework assignment

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:32.580
on Rydberg atoms
in such cavities.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:35.660
The other example is
in the optical domain.

00:10:43.970 --> 00:10:48.470
And this really involves
the D line of alkali atoms.

00:10:48.470 --> 00:10:50.490
You drive them on the D line.

00:10:50.490 --> 00:10:53.470
rubidium and caesium
are often used,

00:10:53.470 --> 00:10:56.490
and the work is enabled
by the development

00:10:56.490 --> 00:10:59.700
of so-called supermirrors
which have an extremely

00:10:59.700 --> 00:11:05.360
high reflectivity, and you can
realize an excellent q factor.

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:09.560
And the leaders in this field
are Jeff Kimble and Gerhard

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:12.720
Rempe at the Max
Planck Institute.

00:11:12.720 --> 00:11:17.230
So let me just
discuss an example

00:11:17.230 --> 00:11:19.660
taken from the optical domain.

00:11:19.660 --> 00:11:28.130
So the generic
situation is that you

00:11:28.130 --> 00:11:35.410
have two mirrors which
define a single mode cavity.

00:11:35.410 --> 00:11:40.120
Usually, you have
a stream of atoms.

00:11:40.120 --> 00:11:42.390
Traditionally in
atomic beams, then

00:11:42.390 --> 00:11:46.230
in some experiments in slowed
atomic beams, more recently

00:11:46.230 --> 00:11:49.260
in atoms which are
falling out off the mode,

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:52.870
and only very recently
single atoms with the help

00:11:52.870 --> 00:11:56.550
of other laser beams that are
trapped inside the cavity.

00:11:56.550 --> 00:11:58.590
So they are streamed
in such a way

00:11:58.590 --> 00:12:03.630
that only one or a few atoms
are in the mode volume interact

00:12:03.630 --> 00:12:06.800
with a single mode of the
cavity at a given time.

00:12:06.800 --> 00:12:12.270
And then you want to figure
out what is now happening,

00:12:12.270 --> 00:12:17.790
and you have the probe laser,
you send it through the cavity,

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:23.260
and then you record the
transmission with a photodiode.

00:12:23.260 --> 00:12:23.982
Yanosh?

00:12:23.982 --> 00:12:28.320
AUDIENCE: What is the mirror
made of for the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:31.320
PROFESSOR: The mirror is
made of a glass substrate,

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:33.500
but then you would
[INAUDIBLE] the coating.

00:12:33.500 --> 00:12:36.110
And the mastering is
really to put coatings

00:12:36.110 --> 00:12:39.310
on which are very
pure, but then also I

00:12:39.310 --> 00:12:43.150
think using ion
sputtering, you make

00:12:43.150 --> 00:12:45.750
sure that the coating
is extremely smooth

00:12:45.750 --> 00:12:48.930
and does not have any
surface irregularities which

00:12:48.930 --> 00:12:52.130
would scatter a tiny
fraction of the light.

00:12:52.130 --> 00:12:55.030
I know there are some people
in Ike's group and [INAUDIBLE]

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:56.760
group who work with
high q mirrors.

00:12:56.760 --> 00:13:00.280
What is a typical example
for the reflectivity?

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:02.146
Or the q factor you can reach?

00:13:02.146 --> 00:13:07.006
AUDIENCE: 5 [INAUDIBLE] and
a finesse of, maybe, 500,000.

00:13:07.006 --> 00:13:09.440
And they're called
superpolished mirrors.

00:13:09.440 --> 00:13:12.110
PROFESSOR: So finesse of
about a million, and that

00:13:12.110 --> 00:13:16.480
means the mirrors have
99.9999% reflectivity.

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:20.140
And the superpolishing, I
think, that was the last step.

00:13:20.140 --> 00:13:22.100
People had controlled
the materials,

00:13:22.100 --> 00:13:24.810
but then they found ways
to make a super polish

00:13:24.810 --> 00:13:27.830
and avoid these even
one part per million

00:13:27.830 --> 00:13:31.184
scattering by surface roughness.

00:13:33.741 --> 00:13:34.240
OK.

00:13:34.240 --> 00:13:37.590
So if you do that experiment,
what would you expect?

00:13:37.590 --> 00:13:40.250
Well, it's a
[INAUDIBLE] experiment

00:13:40.250 --> 00:13:46.440
so if you would scan
the probe laser,

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:48.580
and there is nothing
in it, what you

00:13:48.580 --> 00:13:54.610
would expect is you would
just expect a transmission

00:13:54.610 --> 00:13:57.180
peak at the cavity resonance.

00:13:57.180 --> 00:13:59.270
And if you tune
much further, you

00:13:59.270 --> 00:14:03.030
get the next peak at
the free spectral range.

00:14:03.030 --> 00:14:05.400
Let me just indicate that.

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:09.230
So this is a case for
0 atoms in the cavity.

00:14:09.230 --> 00:14:11.820
If you put 1 photon
in the cavity,

00:14:11.820 --> 00:14:14.770
you no longer-- sorry,
1 atom in the cavity,

00:14:14.770 --> 00:14:17.620
you're no longer
probing a cavity,

00:14:17.620 --> 00:14:19.790
you're really probing
a system, which

00:14:19.790 --> 00:14:21.510
is no longer the
cavity by itself.

00:14:21.510 --> 00:14:23.390
It's an atom-photon system.

00:14:23.390 --> 00:14:25.110
It's a couple system.

00:14:25.110 --> 00:14:28.580
And we know it's described by
our two-by-two Hamiltonian,

00:14:28.580 --> 00:14:32.060
and this Hamiltonian
has two solutions.

00:14:32.060 --> 00:14:36.670
And the two solutions are
split by the one photon Rabi

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:37.770
frequency.

00:14:37.770 --> 00:14:40.550
So the two eigenvalues
of our Hamiltonian

00:14:40.550 --> 00:14:46.100
are at plus minus
omega 1 photon.

00:14:46.100 --> 00:14:50.730
So therefore, for n equals
1, we have a situation

00:14:50.730 --> 00:14:56.520
that we have two peaks split
by the single photon Rabi

00:14:56.520 --> 00:14:58.190
frequency.

00:14:58.190 --> 00:15:00.540
Of course, I have assumed
that great care has

00:15:00.540 --> 00:15:04.570
been spent to make sure that
the cavity resonance is right

00:15:04.570 --> 00:15:07.290
where the atomic resonance is.

00:15:07.290 --> 00:15:10.370
So this is now for 1.

00:15:10.370 --> 00:15:15.840
If you have 10 atoms, remember
the two-by-two Hamiltonian

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:19.920
looks the same, but it has the
square root n plus 1 factor.

00:15:19.920 --> 00:15:24.150
So neglecting the 1 roughly when
we have 10 atoms in the cavity,

00:15:24.150 --> 00:15:27.980
it's square root 10
larger Rabi frequency.

00:15:27.980 --> 00:15:30.680
And therefore, we
would expect that we

00:15:30.680 --> 00:15:34.390
have now a splitting
of the two modes, which

00:15:34.390 --> 00:15:37.110
is square root 10 plus 1 larger.

00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:46.220
Actually, I didn't-- sorry,
I have to collect myself now.

00:15:50.538 --> 00:15:54.200
I showed you that
the Rabi frequency

00:15:54.200 --> 00:15:58.670
scales with square root n
plus 1 in the photon field.

00:15:58.670 --> 00:16:00.880
But you should realize
that everything

00:16:00.880 --> 00:16:02.950
is [? isometric ?]
between photons and atoms.

00:16:02.950 --> 00:16:06.180
It's the complete coupling
between photons and atoms.

00:16:06.180 --> 00:16:10.110
And if you would now look--
but I don't want to do it now--

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:13.530
if you would now look what
happens if several atoms are

00:16:13.530 --> 00:16:16.000
present in the mode
volume, you would also

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:21.450
get a scaling which is n
plus 1 in the atom number,

00:16:21.450 --> 00:16:23.840
because the atom
coupled coherently.

00:16:23.840 --> 00:16:25.910
It is actually an effect
of super-radiance,

00:16:25.910 --> 00:16:27.380
which we'll discussed later.

00:16:27.380 --> 00:16:29.250
So just take my word.

00:16:29.250 --> 00:16:32.170
You have the same scaling
with the atom number.

00:16:32.170 --> 00:16:35.870
But I have to give you my word
now, because in the experiment

00:16:35.870 --> 00:16:37.005
this is what people varied.

00:16:40.810 --> 00:16:44.280
AUDIENCE: If they had varied
power or number of photons

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:47.380
instead, like, we couldn't
have drawn these same diagrams,

00:16:47.380 --> 00:16:47.880
right?

00:16:47.880 --> 00:16:52.906
Because then the top part
of the Lorentzian changes.

00:16:52.906 --> 00:16:57.840
If you're changing the photon
number then Lorentzians change.

00:16:57.840 --> 00:16:58.790
PROFESSOR: Say again?

00:16:58.790 --> 00:17:00.920
AUDIENCE: So, like,
right now, yes, we

00:17:00.920 --> 00:17:02.760
are varying the
number of atoms so we

00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:04.930
can talk about the splitting.

00:17:04.930 --> 00:17:07.773
But if we were varying the
power or the number of photons

00:17:07.773 --> 00:17:09.942
instead, then each
of the Lorentzians,

00:17:09.942 --> 00:17:11.250
